charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
There are currently 2.5 million people living with cancer in the UK, and this is set to grow to almost 4 million by 2030.

Over the next three years, were aiming to raise £500,000. This amount could fund 25,000 hours of care from health professionals, supporting over 1,500 people affected by cancer. Already Warner Leisure Hotels are on the way to achieving this total, raising over £100,000 during the first five months of the partnership.

Team members have launched themselves into fundraising by trekking mountains, running marathons, cycling and even climbing over Londons iconic O2 Arena.

In addition to team members taking part in brilliant activities, Warner have been engaging their guests with our messaging and exciting fundraising events. They have a full and exciting calendar of fundraising activity planned, including a 'Go Mad Go Green' event, charity walks, entertainment evenings, and coffee mornings.

eventName: The Bluebell and Higgledy Half Marathon
story:
Ahoy there!

During the pandemic, Macmillan Cancer Care took a massive 50% hit in income. Higgledy Garden is teaming up with Bluebell Cottage Gardens to run/walk/shuffle/stagger/hop/boing/dribble our way around a 13.1 mile course on Easter Sunday in order to help our chums at MacMillan.

We know things are tight for many of us right but now but any amount of cash is, of course, helpful.

The team will be made up of fewer than six athletes (and a dog)....all in peak physical fitness...ready to take on this grueling challenge. We will keep you updated as we go, with photos, videos and general banter.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I have set myself a challenge to ride 400 Kilometres,
roughly 250 miles on my mountain bike. At least 80% of the rides I complete will take place off road making my trails more interesting and a challenge.

This will take place throughout April, starting on Thursday
1st April and finishing Friday 31st April 2021.

I am doing this to raise money for MacMillan Cancer support.
The reason I have chosen this particular charity for this event is because sadly my Nan passed away with cancer recently and this great charity helped my Nan and Grandad in the final stages of her life. They are still supporting my Grandad now which makes them extra special to me.

My family and people close to me have had their lives affected
by cancer, so I would like to do something to give back and help others that need it. Loved ones will never be forgotten.

I have never done anything like this before, just a gentle
family bike ride to enjoy the outdoors and scenery. My chosen charity supports many people who are affected, so my drive and motivation from them, myself and others will make me do my best to achieve my target. I have an aim to try and raise £500.00 so it will be £2 for every mile I ride. Any donations of any amount will be hugely appreciated and I will be incredibly grateful.

I don’t have social media so I will be documenting all my
rides on three family members Facebook accounts (jackie.rolstone) (jo.rolstone) (sam.hicks.1257604) and keeping everyone updated with how the fundraising is going.

Many Thanks for your support

Andy

Starting April 1st we will be doing 100 squats a day for The whole month! Giving LIVE videos for others to join in...

And for every month up until our 26mile walk in September we are going to fundraise by achieving something new or have some raffles, attend some events, so please follow our fundraising journey whilst we make it fun for everyone!! ...

Love Sian & Terri

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: Ibstock 2 Whitby Riders For British Heart Foundation
story: We are a team of over 50s riding in memory of our dear friend Tony Bradbury. Our aim is to cycle from Ibstock to Whitby some 180 miles on June 24th/25th. Some of us have not ridden a bike for years let alone anything of this distance, combined with our age and fitness this is going to be a big challenge. So to give us that incentive and drive we will cycle and try to raise a few quid for the British Heart Foundation in memory of Tony who sadly passed away in 2019. We are not setting a target as anything we can raise between us will be greatly appreciated in these difficult times for life saving charities. Many thanks for your support from all of the silly buggers taking part in this challenge.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit Judy's memorial page. 

Judy was mum to Simon, Debs and Vanessa, and a wonderful grandma to Erin Jess Charlie Cas and Izzie.  She was also a very proud great-grandma to little Eric and our new 'bump to be'.  Sadly, Judy passed away on the 13th of March this year. The Guide Dogs was her favourite charity and every time she received an update from them, particularly about Spencer the black labrador, she was so delighted, and shared all of Spencer's news with us.  

I know that mum would be pleased to raise funds for this worthwhile charity, so if you would like to donate here instead of flowers in mum's memory, I know she would be smiling at us right now.

Please contact our group via email or
Facebook

Please state your name, contact number, address and
post code

 Which cookies you would like to order

And whether you would like to enter
our prize draw

Please then donate to our Just Give page stating you’re name, what bakes you have ordered
and if you have entered our prize draw

All bakes will be delivered the
weekend of April 17th & 18th

 Unless other individual arrangements have been
made

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Anyone who knows me, knows how much I just don't exercise! 

Well, I've decided I have to change all that and help raise some pennies for a wonderful cause at the same time. 

I've been a volunteer for Guide Dogs for the past 8 years, fundraising, taking Guide Dogs for their well-deserved free- running down-time and also as a 'My Guide', helping people with varying degrees of sight loss find their way around their local areas. 

So, I'm taking part in the sponsored step challenge that's good for the sole! I will be stepping it up in my chosen week this May to raise vital funds for Guide Dogs! 

The sponsorship money you help me raise really will make a difference. Just £95 could buy a training school kit for one guide dog trainer who will teach pups the special skills they need as fully qualified guide dog. 

Go on - help me knock my socks off!

story:
As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.

It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. 

By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
The sponsored walk thats good for the sole.

Your small steps will help Guide Dogs make giant leaps. Just one week of stepping can make a difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. Raise over £50 (£25 for children) and well replace those worn out socks with a brand-new Guide Dogs pair designed by an international fashion icon!

How your funds will change lives...

-	£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-	£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-	£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-	£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.

Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

I have committed to walk 70,000 steps between the 10th and 16th of May 2021, please help me support Guide Dogs. Everyone deserves to have a happy life and all guide dogs deserve to be looked after and made sure they are trained properly. 

Please see below a statement from the charity and what can be achieved with your help: 

The sponsored walk that's good for the sole.Small steps will help Guide Dogs make giant leaps. Just one week of stepping can make a difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. Raise over £50 (£25 for children) and well replace those worn out socks with a brand-new Guide Dogs pair! How your funds will change lives...

-£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. 

So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

-	£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-	£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-	£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-	£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.

Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation. 

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss. 

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society. 

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

story: Im Geeking out for GOSH and taking on a gaming challenge to raise money for the seriously ill children and their families at Great Ormond Street Hospital. They need us now, more than ever. For any parent, it is a worrying time when your child needs hospital treatment. But if your child is seriously ill, in the middle of a pandemic, this is even more daunting. With infection control restrictions on parents staying with their children, worry around travelling safely to and from hospital and being treated by staff in protective clothing, what is already a stressful time is even more challenging. Your support could help fund services like the hospitals incredible Play team, Social Work Service and multi-faith chaplaincy team, as well as funding family accommodation so mums and dads stay near their children. It'll also keep me going and give me the power-up I need to complete this challenge. Its quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the give now button on the right. Thanks!

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit this JustGiving page.

Lucian Barclay Rebera was born in Dehiwela, Ceylon on the 21st July, 1945. He was keen on music from an early age, and taught himself the piano. Blessed with a good voice, he was often asked to play and sing at family gatherings and parties. An innate talent enabled him to master the saxophone and melodica, until he eventually discovered his passion: the bass guitar.

He delighted family, friends, and audiences performing with his band at many gigs over the years.

He won't play for us again, but his love is in our hearts, and his song in our memories forever.

RIP Dearest Lucian. Husband, father, grandfather, great grandfather, brother and friend.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This page is created in memory of Jen Baker who was suddenly taken from us on 23rd October 2020. 

Jen and her twin Cath have been my best friends for as long as I can remember. I’ve had them both by my side from Primary School, through High School, 6th Form and all through adult life. They’re the kindest, most thoughtful people I know, and I’ve always known how lucky I was to have them by my side.  

Jen was such a hardworking person who cared so much for everyone. Many of us were lucky enough to call her a friend. Having Jen as a friend meant you had someone always rooting for you and wanting the very best for you. She had a bright future and we would always talk about the fun that lays ahead. Then all of a sudden that was taken. Five months have now passed and it’s still impossibly hard to wrap our heads round all this. 

It’s heartbreaking that someone so deserving of so much happiness had it all taken away. 

The pain is deep because the love is deep, I can’t put into words the remarkable person Jen was. 

To try to focus on something and do something in memory of Jen I’m doing a half marathon every month and the London Marathon in October. I’m raising money for Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) because of the life saving treatment they gave Jen as a baby. Without their treatment, we wouldn’t have been lucky enough to have Jen in our lives so this is to say thank you and it’s a charity Jen was grateful for.

Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

On Sunday 12 September I will be running the GNR in Newcastle for Great Ormond Street Children’s Hospital Charity fund. Thank you to those who had already sponsored me for last years cancelled event - that money rolls over into this event.

Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive for life-changing treatments. Despite the greatest challenges a child can face, the hospital is a place where being sick does not always mean being sad. And it’s a place where you’ll find – today and every day – some of the bravest people you could ever meet.

This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support, and every day is a chance for you to make a difference.

Over the weekend of 21-23rd May I will be taking on the crazy challenge started by David Goggins - Run 4 miles every 4 hours for 48 hours.

Whilst I won’t be asking you to join in the whole challenge, you can sign up for a ‘wave’ starting at 6pm on Friday 21 May when you can run/jog/walk 4 miles at your own pace. The next ‘waves’ will be 10pm, 2am, 6am, 10am, 2pm etc so choose a time to suit you. Hopefully we can share some live coverage!!

Adhering to COVID guidance at the time, small groups may be able to go out together physically and I am hoping some of you may be able to join me in Stanton to keep me going!

For a suggested minimum £10 donation you will get a GOSH medal. Half of the profits will go to Sarah Dunsdon’s Bowel Cancer Mega May challenge and half to GOSH.

For an extra £2 I am asking you to guess how long it will take for me to run 48 miles over 48 hours. For the mathematicians amongst you, my average time per KM is 7 minutes and bear in mind I will more than likely get slower as time goes on!! You can guess any time between 10 hours and 14 hours.

The winner of the sweepstake will get half of the prize money with the rest going to GOSH.

If you would like to take part then message me your name and address (for the medal) and I will send bank transfer details. or via paypal at joymhart@outlook.com

https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/joy-hart2?newPage=True

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Rube will be cycling 4 miles everyday for the entire month of April , totalling 120 miles in a month. Read the below and please help us to bring this new lifeboat home to Looe. Rube see’s how unbelievable the crew of the RNLI are and how they put their own lives at risk to save other. When Rube grows up her dream is to be a beach lifeguard and then hopefully into  RNLI crew herself. 

In 2010 the D-Class Inshore Lifeboat Ollie Naismith was officially named and went on service at Looe. The lifeboat was named after a popular local teenager Ollie Naismith who sadly died in a tragic road traffic accident in 2009. Ollies parents, Maxine and John Naismith spearheaded a fundraising campaign to raise the funds for the lifeboat which has gone on to save many lives in and around Looe including the life of Louis Webber, a young local lad who was of a similar age to Ollie. The lifeboat is now coming to the end of its operational life so the team at Looe Lifeboat station are teaming up with the Naismiths and Webber family to launch the Looe Lifeboat Appeal to raise the £78,000 required to provide a replacement lifeboat which will be named the Ollie Naismith II.Your donation to this community appeal will help to fund this lifeboat which will continue the selfless work of our volunteer lifeboat crew in Looe.

story:
This year I’m going to be giving up my birthday for a great cause that’s close to my heart. Please, no gifts or cards, show your support for RNLI Weston-super-Mare with me instead. Just 12 days after my birthday last year, they saved my life without any doubt.

I wouldn’t be here celebrating another year (as shitty as it may have been in other respects!) if it weren’t for their quick actions & selfless acts, fishing me out the water just at the right time. They could have been spending time with their families, or just getting on with their lives without putting themselves in harms way, instead, the volunteer crew in Weston-Super-Mare go out into the sea, and navigate extreme & often deadly conditions to save sorry ass’s like mine who are caught out so easily by the tide.

My special thank-you goes to the lifeboat crew on the day, Liam McDermott (Helm), Paul Sargent and Dave Ridout, who were there for me and saved me.

So yeah... I’m lucky enough to be here today and that is the best gift I could ever wish for.


The link below has been specially customised and will take you to the RNLI Weston-super-Mare's Justgiving site, where you can donate to my fundraiser directly. Any financial support will be very appreciated by the volunteers and will help them to continue to save lives at sea.

RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
The RNLI has answered mayday calls for nearly 200 years, from those called from sinking fishing boats, to families swimming on busy beaches, to dog walkers cut off by the tide. It's the most urgent plea, used by mariners when life is in immediate danger and when their lifesavers hear those words they launch courageously into the unknown to help those who rely on their help.

This May, as summer approaches, they're the ones sending out a mayday call. As we look forward to 2021 and beyond, they know that they'll be facing the busiest summer season for the lifesavers to come. And to keep them safe, ready and knowing they can handle whatever the summer brings, they need our help.

They're counting on us to answer their call and take on the Mayday Mile. Our support will help the crew stand strong as our busiest summer season approaches.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
100k hike – sure thing!


Including a 2170m climb – why not?


No sleep included? Hmm...


Great, all signed up! – oh s**t really!?


But its for the animals!


LET’S DO THIS!!! 💪🏻



Hi guys! On the 4th-5th September we are taking part in the South Coast Ultra Challenge in support of the World Wide Fund for Nature, WWF.


During this challenge we will attempt to hike the 100k from Eastbourne to Arundel and will climb 2170 metres (its tiring just typing that!) This is a non stop challenge so we will be walking through the day and night over a 24 hour+ period.


Why would we do this!?


To be honest there are multiple reasons why we have chosen to take on such a huge challenge, but here's just a few:


* 2020s catastrophic Australian bushfires - 3 billion animals were affected, including 30% of the entire koala population in mid-north coast of New South Wales, worsening the extinction crisis the country was already facing. We would love to donate towards protecting the remaining wildlife and species rehabilitation efforts.


* To give our mental health some much needed TLC! With one of us shielding and one living alone, like so many others we have both struggled for different reasons with our mental health throughout the duration of the UKs Covid-19 lockdowns. We are taking part in this challenge together to have a shared goal and something to train for and work towards


* We both have such genuine love and admiration for the planet and all the species we share it with. We are in a global crisis and we feel passionate about raising awareness and joining the fight against climate change and future proofing wildlife.


Thank you so much for taking the time to read through our story. If you are able to and would like to make a donation towards our challenge we would be truly grateful - it will make the months of hard training and lots of suffering worth it!


If you also have the time, please follow the link below to learn some more about the amazing work WWF are doing :)


https://www.wwf.org.uk/


We look forward to sharing our journey with you all.


Thank you, and stay safe and positive!


Lauren + Paige

We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Trailwalker UK supports the incredible work of both Oxfam Great Britain and The Gurkha Welfare Trust.

We are keen to take on a challenge of this long distance walk together to give us a positive goal to focus on after this past year. This is not a group midlife crisis - we have been running, cycling and walking together for the past 10 years but the farthest we've gone together is a marathon - this will be a  new challenge because it is a nonstop   walk through the night and probably long into the next day.

Everyone knows that living in the UK through the pandemic has been hard this past year but it is nothing like the difficulties faced by the people of Yemen after 6 years of war. Oxfam is appealing for money to help with this crisis. 

Oxfam is also helping tackle the effects of coronovirus throughout the world- https://www.oxfam.org.uk/oxfam-in-action/responding-coronavirus/

Trailwalker also raises money for The Gurkha Welfare Trust via Oxfam - https://oxfamapps.org/trailwalker/gwt.php. Without Oxfam's support these veterans, their families and communities would struggle for medical care, money and even clean water. 

Please support us in our fundraising efforts for these important causes. We will do our best to support each other to tackle the distance in good humour and share the ups and downs with you. We have already stocked up on blisters pads and ibuprofen gel!

story:
Thanks for visiting my Just Giving Page 

I'm Harry and I'm 6 years old. Last week, I saw the Water Aid advert on the TV and it made me feel sad. I spoke to my Mummy about it because, “it makes me feel bad that some people only have dirty water.”

I was hoping I could send some clean water from my tap to the children I had seen on the advert, I actually filled a few jugs but Mummy explained it wasn’t that easy to send water in the post. 

Instead, she said I could raise funds for Water Aid, an amazing organisation who will use the money I raise to help the children I saw.

I thought about doing a sponsored dance or baking some cakes, mummy liked the idea of a sponsored silence but I didn't!  

Finally I decided I would complete a special ‘water walk' carrying 4 litres of water for 1 mile. I'm quite nervous as I've never done anything like this before but also excited because I really want to help. 

I am going to do the walk on Friday 2nd April at 11am please help me to help other children who deserve to have clean water. 

Thank you.

Harry age 6 (almost 7)

story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Although being able to have clean water, reliable toilets
and good hygiene seems like a normal part of daily life for everyone, billions
of people do not have access to these basic needs. 1 in 10 people are unable to
access clean water close to home and 1 in 4 people don’t have a decent toilet
of their own. Individuals are forced to drink, bathe, cook and clean with dirty
water, risking their health every day in order to survive. In addition to this
lack of hygiene, many children have to walk over 5 miles every morning just to
collect water for the day, this is time that could otherwise be used for
learning.

Water Aid has teams in 28 countries across the world working
to transform millions of lives every year by improving access to clean water,
toilets and hygiene. They directly install taps, toilets and wells in areas of
need along with proving funds for education and convincing governments to
change laws.

Thank you for donating – every pound makes a difference.
Chloe.
